Anonymous Tue 25 Jun 2024 17:13:50 No.66898834 Report
Quoted By: >>66898894
>>66898428
dw, brainwashing people about tech is my favorite past time.

A hypervisor is what sets up virtual machines, "PC's within a PC'. So you can do things like try out various Linux distros under Windows.

Type 1 is closer to your PC's hardware so whatever you want to run under that, it would have to be able to run on "bare metal", so as if you installed it instead of your current OS, that way it has more performance.

Type 2 is a bit higher and "makes up" a PC, which is lower performance, but allows for running OS' that would otherwise not play nice with your hardware, like Windows XP, and then do tricks like making up a GPU so you can play older games on it.

This is something VMware Workstation Pro, a Type 2 hypervisor does and I tend to use it for more than just running modern OS'. Now, for it to have better performance, it needs VMX CPU instructions. This is something on the hardware level that is a must for good virtualization performance.

The issue with Windows is that both Hyper-V and Docker rely on a system component by the name of "Windows Hypervisor Platform". Once you have that installed and running, it takes away access to those instructions from anything that's not using Windows Hypervisor Platform, and VMware doesn't really use that or works well with that. Basically it's a VMware issue in my use case, it's either Hyper-V and Docker or VMware, because VMware can't play nice.

Oh yeah, all of this that I mentioned is just about running full operating systems. Docker containers are a different thing. More practical than OS virtualization, but again, those pesky VMX instructions.
